@node play "The game: Installation/Playing"

                             Installation

  The installation is very simple, just place "Create_a_Q" where you
want on your hard drive, floppy disk, Ram Disk, etc. No other files or
Libraries are needed.

                             How to play?

  The game play is simple: to move a peg (a circular or rectangular
shape), click on it with the mouse pointer and then click on the empty
space (shape with a small dot) where you want to move the peg. You can
only move a peg 2 spaces horizontally, vertically or diagonally,
depending on which kind of moves are allowed in the 'Allowed Moves' box
at the right of the game board. If the move is possible, the selected
peg will go there.

  In 'Create_a_Q' there are two ways to play:

-The @{b}Normal@{ub} game:   You must jump over a @{b}peg@{ub} and that peg will be
                    removed.

-The @{b}Inverted@{ub} game: You must jump over an @{b}empty space@{ub} and a peg will
                    appear there, just as if you would play the 'Normal'
                    game backward.

  The goal of the game is to remove all the pegs (or fill up the board,
if the game is inverted), until only one peg is left (or only one space
is empty, in the inverted game), preferably where the empty space
(or peg) was located at the start.

  The permitted moves are indicated by icons in the 'Allowed Moves' box.
A move that is not permitted has an 'X' drawn over it. By default, only
the vertical and horizontal moves are allowed.

  When there are no possible moves, the game ends and Create_a_Q will
display how many pegs (or empty spaces for the 'Inverted' game) are
remaining.

  Have fun!

OPTIONS
-------

  When you use Create_a_Q in the 'Game' mode, the following buttons are
shown:

 -@{b}New Game@{ub}:                    Restarts a game.

 -Game Type - @{b}Normal/Inverted@{ub}: This is a toggle button between the
                               'Normal' and the 'Inverted' game.

 -@{b}Q Editor@{ub}:                    Activates the Game board @{" Editor " link qeditor}.

 -@{b}About...@{ub}:                    Displays the informations about
                               Create_a_Q.

@endnode

@node qeditor "Q Editor"

                                 Q Editor

  With the Editor, you can create all the game boards you want. The
editing area is displayed as a 11 x 11 grid. the squares with a black
and white circle are the pegs and the squares with a blue dot are a
potential 'empty space' for the game board.

[Please note that I assume that you are using the default Workbench colour
palette or at least the first 4 colours of the palette (which this game
uses) you are using are the same ones as on the default palette, otherwise
the colours may be different from the ones mentioned in this
documentation...]

  To change a game board, simply click in the grid to add or remove the
shapes you want. Depending on the icon on the 'Place peg/Place empty space'
button, it will place a peg or an empty space there. If you click on a
space occupied by an identical shape (peg or empty space), it will be
erased (toggled On or Off), otherwise it will be replaced by the new shape.

  A potential 'Empty Space' is represented by a blue dot. You can place any
number of these tiles you want on a game board, even fill the entire 11 x 11
grid with them. If you place more than one of these potential 'Empty Spaces',
when you return to the Game mode, or each time you play a game, Create_a_Q
will randomly choose one of these 'empty spaces' and place pegs in the
remaining ones.

  You can also choose the type of moves you want to allow on the game board.
You can allow all of them or you can allow only one type of move. If you
permit the Diagonal moves, in the Game mode, the playing tiles will have an
octagonal shape and the pegs will be round, otherwise, the playing tiles and
pegs will have a rectangular shape.

  Clicking on the 'Play!!' button will allow you to play the edited game
board. If you didn't place at least one empty space, Create_a_Q will place
one randomly so you can play the game board, but it will not place that
empty space on the edited board.

  Also, if you play a game board, and didn't 'permit' any moves (all the
Allowed moves have 'X' shapes on them),  Create_a_Q will remove the 'X'
shapes on the Vertical and Horizontal move icons by default, so the game
board is somewhat playable.

  You cannot play an empty game board! If you click on the 'play' button
and the editing board is empty, Create_a_Q will reset to its default
game board.

  When you click on the 'Cancel' button, Create_a_Q will return to the
Game mode and display the last used game board, and the original allowed
moves will be used.

  You are free to create ANY game board (as long as at least one type of
move is possible, and there is one peg or empty space on the board),
Create_a_Q will not prevent you from playing a particular board because
it is not playable. In fact, Create_a_Q can't verify if a board is
playable, so the limit is only an 11 x 11 grid... and your imagination!

OPTIONS
-------

  In the Editor mode the following buttons are shown:

 -@{b}CLR@{ub}:                  To erase the current game board.

 -@{b}Peg/Empty space icon@{ub}: Toggles between a 'Peg' and a potential 'Empty
                        Space' shape. The 'Peg' is represented by a
                        black and white circle and the 'Empty space' is
                        represented by a small blue dot icon.

 -@{b}Load@{ub}:                 To load a game board, this brings up a requester
                        where you can choose the game board you want
                        to load.

 -@{b}Save@{ub}:                 To save a game board, this brings up a requester
                        where you can enter the file name of the
                        current game board you want to save.

 -@{b}Allowed moves icons@{ub}:  Each type of move can be enabled or disabled
                        just by clicking on its icon. If a move cannot
                        be made, its corresponding icon will have an 'X'
                        on it.

 -@{b}Cancel@{ub}:               Cancel the modifications you made and returns
                        to the Game mode.

 -@{b}Play!!@{ub}:               Exits the editing mode and lets you play the
                        board you created.

 -@{b}About...@{ub}:             Displays the informations about Create_a_Q.

@endnode

